did.abstract: The Hanover Royal Music Archive consists of printed and manuscript music, printed books about music, and related materials assembled by Ernest Augustus, King of Hanover, and his successors. A significant component originated in England and concerns musical activity of several children of George III, circa 1770-1837, particularly Ernest Augustus, then Duke of Cumberland, and Princess Augusta, as well as Prince George of Cumberland, son of Ernest Augustus and later Georg V, King of Hanover. These materials moved to Hanover, apparently circa 1837 when Ernest Augustus succeeded William IV as King of Hanover. In Hanover, the collection was expanded by Ernest Augustus and Georg V, and much of the present content relates to music in the Hanoverian court through the mid-nineteenth century. While most materials date circa 1770-1870, a few items extend this span from the seventeenth through the mid-twentieth century.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: This preliminary finding aid is largely based on a collection-level description and a partial list of contents provided by Sotheby's prior to purchase by the Beinecke Library. Information in item-level descriptions from the Sotheby's list, which generally covered materials originating in Great Britain, has been retained in folder titles in a standardized format. Brief descriptions have been added for contents not listed individually by Sotheby's. Description of features such as marks of ownership, manuscript annotations, accompanying material, and partial contents of bound collections, has been retained in folder notes when noted by Sotheby's. Additional similar information may be found through further examination of the collection.

Some materials were accompanied by notes in German made by a recent former owner or researcher. Most notes were written on notecards or envelopes, which have been retained in a separate series. Additional notes were written directly on some items, and some items bear adhesive residue indicating that notecards were formerly affixed to them. Other evidence of recent use includes at least one instance of accompanying correspondence dating from the 1950s, and undated recent transcriptions of music accompanying some materials in Series III, Duke of Cumberland's Band Archive.

bioghist.head: Historical Notes
bioghist.p: Hanover became an electorate of the Holy Roman Empire in 1692. In 1714, George I succeeded as both King of Great Britain and Elector of Hanover, establishing a personal union of the two titles that continued through the eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries. Hanover became a kingdom in 1814, ruled by George III, King of Great Britain, and his successors George IV and William IV. When William IV was succeeded by Queen Victoria in 1837, the prohibition of female succession under Hanoverian law ended the personal union between Britain and Hanover, and Ernest Augustus, Duke of Cumberland, eighth of fifteen children of George III, became Ernest Augustus, King of Hanover. At the same time, Ernest Augustus's son, Prince George of Cumberland, became Georg, Crown Prince of Hanover. The Crown Prince succeeded his father as Georg V, King of Hanover, in 1851.

Musicians working at the court of George III included Johann Christian Bach, who served as music master to Queen Charlotte, 1763-1782, Johann Samuel Schroeter, and Charles Frederick Horn, who served as music instructor for the princesses, 1789-1812. Both Ernest Augustus and Georg V had strong musical interests: Ernest Augustus employed a private band in England as the Duke of Cumberland, and Georg composed and wrote about music. Georg V apparently continued to compose after moving to Hanover, although injuries to his eyes had resulted in blindness by 1833.

Hanover was annexed by Prussia in 1866, as a consequence of the Austro-Prussian War. Georg V lived the remainder of his life in exile in Austria and France, without renouncing his Hanoverian title. His son, Ernst August (1845-1923), continued to claim succession rights, while holding the title of Duke of Cumberland and Teviotdale. Ernest Augustus was deprived of this title after siding with Germany during Word War I. His son, Ernst August (1887-1953), Duke of Brunswick from 1913, was forced to abdicate in 1918.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Hanover Royal Music Archive consists of printed and manuscript music, printed books about music, and related materials assembled by Ernest Augustus, King of Hanover, and his successors. A significant component originated in England and concerns musical activity of several children of George III, circa 1770-1837, particularly Ernest Augustus, then Duke of Cumberland, and Princess Augusta, as well as Prince George of Cumberland, son of Ernest Augustus and later Georg V, King of Hanover. These materials moved to Hanover, apparently circa 1837 when Ernest Augustus succeeded William IV as King of Hanover. In Hanover, the collection was expanded by Ernest Augustus and Georg V, and much of the present content relates to music in the Hanoverian court through the mid-nineteenth century. While most materials date circa 1770-1870, a few items extend this span from the seventeenth through the mid-twentieth century.

Contents include manuscript and printed music used in performance; manuscript music books and bound collections; music in presentation bindings, inscribed or accompanied by letters from composers to Ernest Augustus, Georg V, or other royal family members; and books about music theory and pedagogy. Many genres of music are present, with concentrations in song, collections of national songs of Great Britain and Ireland, solo keyboard, chamber ensemble parts, sacred vocal music scores and parts, opera in vocal score, military band parts, and keyboard and ensemble music for marches, waltzes, and other social dance. Music of a wide range of both major and lesser-known composers active in England, Germany, and elsewhere in Europe during the eighteenth through mid-nineteenth century is present, including early printed editions of Johann Christian Bach, Haydn, Clementi, Mozart, Beethoven, Weber, Rossini, Berlioz, Johann Strauss, Sr., Mendelssohn. Many items bear marks of ownership, including presentation inscriptions, signatures, annotations, shelf mark labels, stamps, personalized and presentation bindings, and accompanying correspondence.

Among materials originating in England are manuscript music books of Princess Augusta and other royal family members, containing holograph music of Johann Christian Bach and Charles Frederick Horn, and an extensive archive of music performed by a private band employed by Ernest Augustus while Duke of Cumberland. Most material added in Hanover consists of presentation copies of music dedicated to Georg V; Hanoverian and Prussian military band music; literary papers, music drafts, and published music of Georg V; and music performed by the Hof- and Kirchenchor, including an archive of manuscript liturgical music. Later additions to the collection include music dedicated to Ernst August (1845-1923) and to members of the Prussian royal family. Additions dated circa 1860s-1910s are predominantly sacred music, indicating that the collection may have remained in use by church musicians during that period.

The archive documents music of the British and Hanoverian royal courts during the period of its accumulation, and is a resource for study of individual music manuscripts and rare publications. Materials originating in Great Britain are related to content dating from the same time period in the British Library's Royal Music Library of Great Britain, and may be found to fill gaps in that larger collection. Several strengths of the Hanover collection are the smaller archives contained within it, particularly music of the Duke of Cumberland's band, Hanover liturgical manuscripts, and music and literary papers of Georg V. Aspects of broad research value include: Johann Christian Bach and his circle; other individual composers and their published and unpublished work; music in the royal courts of Great Britain and Hanover; members of the British and Hanoverian royal families; composition, music education, and professional and amateur performance and employment of musicians in England and Germany; and manuscript copying, music printing, binding practices, and the music trade.

Folder titles for music are in a standardized format, consisting of the following as appropriate: truncated transcribed title; type of score and list of parts; holograph, manuscript, or print; and place and publisher. Contents not listed individually by Sotheby's have been described briefly, usually as "music," either manuscript or print. For all contents, full names and birth/death dates in headings have been supplied, if found in the Library of Congress Authority File or The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians, or in materials in the collection. While these names are generally of composers or authors, some materials are listed under arrangers, editors, or compilers, in conformance with original folders or shelfmark labels.

Much of the manuscript material is copyist's manuscript; some holograph manuscripts have been identified, and others are likely present. Most printed music is engraved, unless noted as typeset or lithograph. Full or partial uniform titles have been added to some folder titles, and some see/see also references have been supplied. Vocal and instrumental parts are listed as found, with no attempt to determine if sets are complete. The following abbreviations have been used in lists of parts:

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Composers represented in this series include many musicians associated with the British and Hanoverian courts. Among earlier materials originating in England is music by Johann Christian Bach and musicians of his circle, including Montague Corri, Charles Egan, Charles Frederick Horn, Charles Edward Horn, Joseph Kemp, Augustus Frederic Christopher Kollmann, Frederick Nicolay, Christopher Papendiek, Johann Samuel Schroeter, William Southbrook, and Charles Wesley. Hanoverian musicians include Georg von Bredow, Julius Gerold, Andreas Hammerschmidt, Heinrich Heidrich, August Lang, and Wilhelm Westmayer. Also present are many works and arrangements by military band musicians. Manuscripts of Georg V include drafts and fair copies of his music, lists of his works, and drafts for a theoretical work, Ideen und Betrachtungen über die Eigenschaften der Musik. Composers such as Beethoven, Clementi, Haydn, Mozart, Rossini, Johann Strauss, Sr., Weber, Berlioz and Mendelssohn are represented by early printed editions or copyist's manuscripts. Early editions of parts for Haydn symphonies are present, some with manuscript cancels or additions in unidentified hands. Some composers in this series may also be found in Series III, Duke of Cumberland's Band Archive, and Series IV. Hanover Liturgical Manuscripts.

While some marks of provenance of individual items are indicated in folder notes, the collection contains extensive additional evidence of ownership and use, including control signatures of composers and publishers indicating ownership of copyright, manuscript inscriptions and performance annotations, manuscript music cancels and additions, personalized bindings, presentation bindings, and dedication inscriptions and related correspondence. Most evidence of provenance relates to Ernest Augustus, Princess Augusta, Princess Amelia, and Georg V. Also present is music dedicated to Queen Charlotte, George IV, Queen Victoria, Ernst August (1845-1923), the Duke of Braunschweig and Lüneburg, and Wilhelm I, King of Prussia.

Following materials organized by name is music by unidentified composers, subarranged for voice, keyboard, and instrumental ensemble. A small amount of other papers contains printed ephemera relating to concerts, church services, and other events; manuscript notes; and detached shelf mark labels and other binding fragments.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Series II, Music Collections, is organized in three subseries: Print Music Collections and Series, Manuscript Music Books, and Bound Collections.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Printed collections consist of series such as publications of the Musical Antiquarian Society and Sammlung von Märschen zum bestimmten Gebrauch der Königlich Preussischen Armée, as well as volumes of music by multiple composers; collections of psalms, chorales and other sacred vocal music; annual keepsakes; and bound journals. Manuscript Music Books are volumes kept by Princess Augusta, Princess Amelia, or other royal family members, containing exercises and copies of vocal and keyboard music. Also present is a volume of music exercises kept by astronomer Caroline Lucretia Herschel. Among the contents of these volumes are a Johann Christian Bach holograph setting of "The Expiring Christian to His Soul," and holograph music of Charles Frederick Horn.

Bound Collections contain printed vocal and keyboard music. Some volumes also contain manuscript material, including a Johann Christian Bach holograph of "T'adoro te solo eterno mio Dio," a version of the aria from his oratorio Gioas, rè di Giuda. Partial contents for some bound collections are listed in folder notes. Further examination of the contents of music books and bound collections is necessary for complete description of their contents. Volumes in this series contain music by multiple composers; additional bound collections in Series I, General Music and Books About Music, contain music by single composers.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Series III, Duke of Cumberland's Band Archive, is organized by name of composer or arranger, and alphabetically by title within each name.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Music consists of sets of parts, printed and copyist's manuscripts, used in performance by a private band employed in Great Britain by Ernest Augustus, Duke of Cumberland, later King of Hanover. This material is an apparently intact archive, with original annotated folders for each work, and a bound catalog listing contents. Though most music is undated, watermarks and preliminary conjectured dates span circa 1790-1810. A small amount of dated music extends this span from 1765 to1834. The catalog volume contains 1814 watermarks, as well as unrelated accounts in an unidentified hand, kept in England, 1838-1840.

Most music is for band, typically clarinets, flute, bassoons, serpent, horns, trumpets, trombone, and timpani. Some works include additional woodwind, brass, or percussion, and some are for orchestra with strings, or for chamber ensembles. Much of the music is manuscript arrangements for band of orchestra works, including arrangements of works by Haydn, Mozart, and Beethoven. Also present is print and manuscript music composed for band, chamber ensembles, or orchestra, including a set of orchestral parts for Beethoven's Symphony No. 1, copyist's manuscript, watermarked 1804. Following music organized by composer name are works by unidentified composers, arranged alphabetically by title.

Music is listed under either original composer or arranger, in accordance with annotations on original folders. Numbering on original folders is cited in folder notes, and may correspond to listings in the catalog volume. Many printed parts are annotated in manuscript, and some bear signatures, stamps, performance markings, or manuscript cancels or additions. A few works are accompanied by transcriptions in an unidentified 20th century hand. While some details of description are noted in folder notes, more evidence of use will likely be found through further examination.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Series IV, Hanover Liturgical Manuscripts, is organized in five subseries: Liturgical Year, Other Liturgy, Other Choral Music, Copyists' Manuscripts, and Other Music.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Contents consists of drafts, fair copies, and sets of scores and parts for music apparently performed by the Hanover Hof- and Kirchenchor, 1850s-1860s. Most music is represented by sets of choral parts, usually SSAATTBB, many signed by the singers who used them. Music may have been composed by Arnold Wehner, who served as choir director or Hofkapellmeister during this period. Other manuscript music composed by Wehner is present in the Copyists' Manuscripts subseries and in the General Music and Books About Music series. The General Music and Books About Music series also contains printed sacred music bearing stamps of the Hanover Hof- and Kirchenchor.

Music for the liturgical year is arranged chronologically by festival day. Other liturgical music is arranged alphabetically by type of service, such as royal confirmations or birthdays. Other choral music for unspecified services is arranged by title. Copyists' manuscripts consist of scores and parts for works of identified composers, copied for use in performance. Individual works arranged alphabetically by composer are followed by several sets and collections of music. Many composers present here are also found in the General Music and Books About Music series. Other music consists of unidentified sketches, notes, and unidentified original folders.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Sotheby's Description consists of a collection-level description and a partial list of contents provided by Sotheby's prior to purchase by the Beinecke Library. Unidentified Notes contains notecards and envelopes with notes in German, written in an unidentified hand, which have been removed from individual items in the collection and organized alphabetically by composer or title. Notes generally consist of bibliographic description of individual items, and in some cases include lists of contents or comments on physical condition. Some envelopes were repurposed, and bear unrelated postmarks dating from the 1980s. Additional similar notes were written directly on some items. See Processing Notes for more information.
